# Settings Page in our UI

This is a page in our UI where our Users can view, edit, create, and experiment with Tasks and Knowledge Units (KUs). 

# Page Goals 

* View all Tasks and Knowledge Unites (KUs) as a table  
* Workbench: Be able to create new KUs and Tasks where applicable and to link them together. For example:   
  * Create a new Directive to be added to a Task  
  * Make a new Tool available to a Task  
  * Add entries to an existing Table  
  * Create a new Table  
  * Be able to experiment with the changes to a Task or KU  
    * For example change table X and see how that affects the prior executions of a task  
* Understand how a specific Task is executed, and what knowledge it depends on  
* Quickly navigate from a KU, say, a Table to all the, say, Tasks that use it  
* Trace which Tools are used by decision-making Tasks

# Overview of Tabs in the Page

The page supports the following sub-type of tabs: 

* Structured lists with filtering/grouping (list of all Tasks and KUs)  
* An interactive knowledge graph showing task-to-KU and KU-to-KU relationships  
* A Workbench that allows experimentation  
* An Knowledge Importer Experience allowing you to convert documents to KUs 

With the above sub-types in mind, here is the list of Tabs:

* **Tasks**  
  * Table with expandable rows  
* **KUnits**  
  * Table with expandable rows  
* **Knowledge Graph (Interactive Graph)**  
  * Combined node-link view of Tasks and KUs  
  * Interactions:  
    * Click a Task → highlight used KUs  
    * Click a KU → highlight consuming Tasks  
* **Workbench**   
  * An area where we can edit/create/test KUs and Tasks  
* **Knowledge Unit Importer**  
  * A way to import new Knowledge Units  
  * Example: A PDF containing knowledge about the enterprise is used to update Directives and Tables with new information 

## Tasks View

In this table every row is a task. The rows are expandable. 

Visible Columns 

* Name   
* Description  
* Function  
* Scope  
* Status  
* Last Run Timestamp  
* Last Modified Timestamp   
* Version  
* Owner (user that created it or system)  
* From “Task Execution Runs”  
  * Number of Thumbs Down  
  * Number of Thumbs Up  
  * Total number of runs

The table can be filtered and ordered by any of the given fields above and search bar. The default order is by “Last Modified”.

Pagination is supported. We should allow at least 20 rows per page. 

When a row is clicked it should expand just below it to provide additional details. When that happens, the remaining rows are pushed down to the bottom as needed.

When a row is clicked we show

* All fields (not just the ones visible in the table)  
* Last N execution examples as a table with timestamps, inputs, and outputs  
  * These are all the relevant information collected in the “Task Execution Runs” table  
* Feedback by user  
  * M examples that user has given a thumbs up \+ feedback (default M \= 3\)   
  * M examples the user has given a thumbs down \+ feedback (default M \= 3\)   
* N dependencies as a list (KUs etc.) (default N=5)  
* Show which task depend on it (which tasks will break if we change this)  
  * Transitive list of tasks. This list can grow long; we just show a number and cap it at 5\.  
* Action  
  * Create a workbench session with this task selected

Additional Layout and Workflow Details

* At the top right we have a button to create a new Task  
  * That creates a new empty Workflow Session (and moves you to the workbench experience).

## Knowledge Units View

In this table every row is a different type of KU (table, directive, tool). 

Pagination is supported. We should allow at least 20 rows per page.

The table can be filtered and ordered by any of the given fields above and search bar. The default order is by “Last Modified”.

Visible Columns: 

* Name  
* Description  
* Type: Document, Directive, Table, Tool  
* Origin  
* Owner  
* Creation Timestamp  
* Version  
* Last Modified Timestamp

When a row is clicked it should expand just below it to provide additional details. When that happens, the remaining rows are pushed down to the bottom as needed.

When a row is clicked we show

* Show all fields (not just the ones visible from the tabulated view)  
* The actual content of the Directive and Table (not relevant for Tools)  
* N dependencies as a list (KUs etc.) (default N=5)  
* Show which task depend on it (which tasks will break if we change this)  
  * Transitive list of tasks. This list can grow long; we just show a number and cap it at 5\.  
* Action  
  * Create a workbench session with this KU selected

## Graph View

Bellow we clearly define the types of edges and relationships that will appear in the graph:

- `Task → Directive (uses)`  
- `Task → Table (uses)`  
- `Task → Tool (uses)`  
- `Task → Document (uses)`  
- `Directive → Table (reference)`  
- `Directive → Document (references)`  
- `Directive → Directive (reference)`

Details

* Edges are directed  
* Cycles are not allowed\!  
  * There is a risk of Cycles only with the Directive to Directive edges.  
* The graph is interactive   
  * You can move nodes and edges around to better visualize the graph  
  * When you click on a node it should show summary of the node on a details panel   
    * The panel should open somewhere where is less likely to have parts of the graph rendering, like the upper left corner is a good option  
    * What to show?  
      * Name at the very top  
      * Description  
      * Owner   
      * Last update time  
    * What not to show?  
      * Relationships and dependencies since those are going to be the centerpiece of the graph visualization   
    * What details to show for different Knowledge Unit Types?  
      * Directives: have the first 256 characters or so shown (the react can appear after you manually expand by clicking “...”)  
      * Document: Same as directive only the first part and expand to about twice as much (but avoid showing the whole thing as it can grow long)  
      * Table: Show the table up to 50 entries or so (have a limit on how much we can attempt to show in terms of rows or columns)  
      * Task: The function of the task

## Workbench 

Workbench is a common experience for Tasks and KUs. 

Entry points:

* Visit the Workbench Tab  
  * Initially it should be empty  
  * There may be different “In-Progress” saved sessions to choose from  
  * Else we can search to load a task/KU into workbench (though a search bar that can search through both Tasks and KUs)  
* From the Tasks or KUs page  
  * There is an option (button) to move the selected Tasks or KU to a new Workbench Session. 

Changes to Tasks and KUs are version controller and audited. There should be a way to select and revert to a different version. 

* Diff view  
* System update vs user update  
* Revert  
* Experiment with an older version without reverting

Additional Layout and Workflow Details

* For KUs the workbench it’s simple  
  * You have an editor experience (think VS Code)  
  * Where you can make changes to the active file (directive, document)  
    * For Tables we have a simpler table edit capability  
    * Add a new row or column, delete or edit fields  
  * On the right hand side you have all the versions   
    * Witi the different timestamps   
    * Very similar to Google Docs does versioning  
    * At any time you make any of the previous version to be the active one  
    * Only one version can be the active one  
    * User can create named version  
    * Named versions of KUs can be used in other workbench session when experimenting with a Task  
  * For Documents we can create different chunking strategies, essentially allowing us to have different configurations of a single document.   
    * A same document can have multiple configurations   
    * E.g., with different chunking strategies   
* For Tasks  
  * At the bottom we also have two boxes side-by-side  
    * One for Input  
    * The other for the generated Output  
    * Any version of any of the dependencies can be selected allowing you to test different configurations with Input and Output

## Knowledge Units Importer

An easy way to automatically extract, populate, and update Tables, Documents, and Directives from documents:

* PDFs  
* Website  
* Text  
* …

The process of ingesting a document and automatically (a) extracting new Knowledge Units in the form of Tables and Directives, (b) enhancing existing Knowledge Units (so add new information to existing units). This is a great way to influence knowledge you didn’t even know existed. 

For example, a user may upload a PDF and give a prompt that this PDF represents Crown Jewels. The PDF will be parsed and all assets extracted will automatically be merged into the Table of Crown Jewels. 

The user adds a piece of information in a text box. The system automatically checks to see if this information can be used to improve an existing Table or Directive or create a new one. 

When uploading a new document, we always generate a document KU. The use can decide if they want to keep it or not. 

Additional Layout and Workflow Details

* At the top we have   
  * an option to upload a file (PDF, txt)  
  * link a website (URL)  
  * paste text  
* Multiple files/urls/pasted-text can be selected and remembered   
* An Import button will trigger the extraction of the text   
* In the background we show a progress bar of the extraction and processing of the text  
* After everything is completed the screen is splitted in a 1x3 grid of three boxes  
  * Left box contains all the information added to existing units with their names listed and a count of entries added for tables and the changed text if it’s a directive  
  * Middle box shows a list of new directives created   
  * Right box any information that didn’t fit anywhere   
* The user can edit the changes and click to save the directives/tables created/updated  
  * All newly created Directives and Tables (not the ones edited are automatically added to a new Workbench Session).

